gn=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|96\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"left\" rowspan=\"1\"|''non-album single''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"11\" style=\"font-size: 8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes releases that did not chart.\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.yothuyindi.com.au}}\n* Previous official website: [https://web.archive.org/web/20021125173004/http://www.yothuyindi.com/ archived] from [http://www.yothuyindi.com/ the original] on 25 November 2002\n* [http://www.yolnguboy.com/directory/htm/frameset3.htm The Yolngu]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050717221522/http://www.garma.telstra.com/ Garma Festival home page]\n* Listen to an excerpt of 'Treaty' on [http://aso.gov.au/titles/music/treaty/ australianscreen online].\n* [http://colsearch.nfsa.afc.gov.au/nfsa/search/summary/summary.w3p;adv=yes;group=;groupequals=;page=0;parentid=;query=Number%3A358788%20%7C%20Number%3A356423;querytype=;resCount=10 Yothu Yindi at the National Film and Sound Archive]\n\n{{Geoffrey Gurrumul Yunupingu}}\n{{ARIA Award for Single of the Year 1990s}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yothu Yindi}}\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian musical groups]]\n[[Category:Northern Territory musical groups]]\n[[Category:Yolngu]]\n[[Category:ARIA Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2013]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:2013 disestablishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Dan arndt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eARIA Awards:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yothu_Yindi"}
{"title_page": "Addo Kazianka", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Addo Kazianka\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1936|2|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n'''Addo Kazianka''' (born 16 February 1936) is an Italian [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=25706 |title=Addo Kazianka |accessdate=13 May 2017 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He won stage 12 of the [[1960 Giro d'Italia]].<ref name=\"Giro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/ritfiche.php?ritid=19186 |title=Giro d'Italia 1960 |accessdate=13 May 2017 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling Archives|25706}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kazianka, Addo}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Italian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Addo Kazianka\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1936|2|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n'''Addo Kazianka''' (born 16 February 1936) is an Italian [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=25706 |title=Addo Kazianka |accessdate=13 May 2017 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He won stage 12 of the [[1960 Giro d'Italia]].<ref name=\"Giro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/ritfiche.php?ritid=19186 |title=Giro d'Italia 1960 |accessdate=13 May 2017 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling Archives|25706}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kazianka, Addo}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Italian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addo_Kazianka"}
{"title_page": "Dude\u0219tii Vechi", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Timi\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Timi\u0219 County\n|image_skyline=Star beshenov cyrkva.JPG\n|image_caption=Banat Bulgarian Roman Catholic church in Dude\u0219tii Vechi (''St\u00e1r Bi\u0161nov'')\n|official_name=Dude\u0219tii Vechi\n|other_name=St\u00e1r Bi\u0161nov\n|image_shield=ROU TM Dudestii Vechi CoA.jpg\n|image_map=Dudestii Vechi jud Timis.png\n|leader_name=Bono Cucalan\n|leader_party=PNL\n|area_total_km2=95.64\n|coordinates   = {{coord|46|03|N|20|29|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|https://dudestii-vechi.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Dude\u0219tii Vechi''' ({{lang-bg|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440 \u0411\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432}} / ''Star Beshenov''; [[Banat Bulgarian dialect|Banat Bulgarian]]: ''St\u00e1r Bi\u0161nov'') is a commune in [[Timi\u0219 County]], [[Romania]]. Dude\u0219tii Vechi is mostly populated by [[Banat Bulgarians]] (Pal\u0107ene), a regional minority group of ethnic [[Bulgarians]] that profess [[Roman Catholicism]], who came from northern [[Bulgaria]], and who are descendants of [[Paulicians]] that settled in the area around 1738. At the 2011 census, the total population of the commune numbered 4203 people.\n\n==Name==\nUntil 1968, it was known as ''Be\u0219enova Veche''. In [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], it is known as \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440 \u0411\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432 / ''Star Beshenov'', in [[Banat Bulgarians#Language|Banat Bulgarian]] as ''St\u00e1r Bi\u0161nov'', in [[German language|German]] as ''Altbeschenowa'', in [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] as ''\u00d3beseny\u0151'', and in [[Serbian language|Serbian]] as \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e \u0411\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e / ''Staro Be\u0161enovo''.\n\n==Languages==\nThe commune is officially bilingual, with both [[Romanian language|Romanian]] and [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] being used as working languages on public signage and in administration, education and justice.\n\n==Religion==\nThe majority of the inhabitants are Roman Catholic.\n\n==Villages==\n\nThe commune is composed of three villages: Cheglevici ([[Banat Bulgarian language|Banat Bulgarian]]: ''T\u00e9glivi\u010d'', {{lang-de|Keglewitschhausen}}, {{lang-hu|Keglevichh\u00e1za}}, {{lang-sr|\u041a\u0435\u0433\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b}}), Colonia Bulgar\u0103 and Dude\u0219tii Vechi. It also included [[V\u0103lcani]] village until 2005, when it was split off to form a separate commune.\n\nColonia Bulgar\u0103 ([[Banat Bulgarian language|Banat Bulgarian]]: ''Telepa'', {{lang-de|Bulgarische Kolonie}}, {{lang-hu|Bolgartelep}}) was founded as ''Telepa'' by [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]] [[Banat Bulgarians|Banat Bulgarian]] colonists in 1846. In 1910, it had a population of 714 Bulgarians. In 1930, the population was 830, of which 353 Bulgarians, 338 [[Hungarians]], 123 [[Germans]], 13 [[Romanians]] and 3 [[Romani people|Romani]]. In the 1940 census, the Bulgarians were not recognized as a separate ethnic group by [[Ion Antonescu]]'s regime, and the population was 729, of which 314 \"others\", 295 Hungarians, 107 Germans and 13 Romanians.\n\n==Culture==\nThe school in Dude\u0219tii Vechi was founded in 1745 by the Bulgarian settlers with the help of the Roman Catholic Church. It is the oldest school of the Bulgarian diaspora and the only school in Romania where Bulgarian language is taught to all grades. {{As of|2004}}, education in Bulgarian was optional, but efforts were made to transform the school into a [[bilingual]] one. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070302030726/http://www.standartnews.com/archive/2005/02/21/balkans/index.htm]\n\nThe village also has an imposing Roman Catholic church.\n\n==Population==\n[[Image:South slavs romania.png|thumb|250px|Location of Dude\u0219tii Vechi commune]]\n\nAccording to the 2011 Romanian census, the commune had a population of 4203. Of the inhabitants for whom data were available, 61.1% were [[Banat Bulgarians]], 28.1% [[Romanians]], 5.6% [[Roma in Romania|Roma]], 4% [[Hungarians]] and 0.7% [[Germans]].\n\n==Historical population==\n\n===Table===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Census'''\n! colspan=\"10\" style=\"background:#ffdead;\" | '''Ethnic distribution'''\n|-\n!'''Year'''\n!'''Population'''\n![[Romanians]]\n![[Banat Bulgarians]]\n![[Germans]]\n![[Magyars]]\n![[Romani people|Romani]]\n![[Serbs]]\n![[Jews]]\n![[Slovaks]]\n!'''Other'''\n!'''Unknown'''\n|-\n| 1880\n| 11,690\n| 2,754\n| n.d\n| 1,295\n| 1,101\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| 6,366\n| \n|-\n| 1910\n| 12,638\n| 3,121\n| n.d\n| 1,403\n| 2,152\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| 5,962\n| \n|-\n| 1941\n| 11,334\n| 2,661\n| n.d\n| 1,206\n| 1,187\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| n.d\n| 6,280\n| \n|-\n|-\n| 1948\n| 11,620\n| 2,754\n| 5,771\n| 1,327\n| 1,415\n| 232\n| 53\n| 34\n| 20\n| \n| \n|-\n| 1956\n| 9,653\n| 2,340\n| 5,610\n| 478\n| 995\n| 210\n| 6\n| 5\n| 7\n| \n| \n|-\n| 1977\n| 8,030\n| 2,221\n| 4,669\n| 319\n| 694\n| 109\n| 6\n| 2\n| 5\n| 9\n| \n|-\n| 1992\n| 6,409\n| 1,996\n| 3,633\n| 57\n| 379\n| 305\n| 11\n| 1\n| 9\n| 17\n| \n|-\n| 2002\n| 5,807\n| 2,368\n| 2,987\n| 44\n| 330\n| 62\n| 16\n|\n|\n|\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n| 4,203\n| 1,122\n| 2,439\n| 27\n| 159\n| 222\n|6\n|0\n|6\n|10\n| 212\n|}\n\n===Chart and Table===\n\n{{clear|left}}                                               \n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"margin-right: 1em; font-size: 85%;\"                 \n! colspan=\"9\" style=\"background-color: #BADBAD;\" | Population trend (Growth/Downtrend)\n|-                                                                 \n|colspan=\"8\" |\n\n<timeline>                                                        \nImageSize  = width:450 height:200                                 \nPlotArea   = left:40 right:10 top:10 bottom:20                    \nTimeAxis   = orie